00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:38,000
Our experiences don't all seem to be inside our brain.

240
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:42,000
Your image of me now doesn't seem to be inside your brain,

241
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,000
yet the official view is there's a little rupert somewhere inside your head.

242
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:48,000
And everything else in this room is inside your head.

243
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:50,000
Your experience is inside your brain.

244
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:55,000
I'm suggesting, actually, that vision involves an outward projection of images.

245
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:57,000
What you're seeing is in your mind, but not inside your head.

246
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:02,000
Our minds are extended beyond our brains in the simplest act of perception.

247
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:05,000
I think that we project out the images we're seeing.

248
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:09,000
And these images touch what we're looking at.

249
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:11,000
If I look at you from behind, you don't know I'm there.

250
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:13,000
Could I affect you?

251
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:15,000
Could you feel my gaze?

252
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:17,000
There's a great deal of evidence that people can.

253
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:20,000
The sense of being stared at is an extremely common experience.

254
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:24,000
And recent experimental research suggests it's real.

255
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:26,000
Animals seem to have it too.

256
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:30,000
I think it probably evolved in the context of predator-prey relationships.

257
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:34,000
Prey animals that could feel the gaze of a predator would survive better than those that couldn't.

258
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:38,000
This would lead to a whole new way of thinking about ecological relationships

259
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:42,000
between predators and prey, also about the extent of our minds.

260
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:47,000
If we look at distant stars, I think our minds reach out in a sense to touch those stars

261
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:51,000
and literally extend out over astronomical distances.

262
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:54,000
They're not just inside our heads.

263
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:58,000
Now, it may seem astonishing that this is a topic of debate in the 21st century.

264
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:02,000
We know so little about our own minds that where our images are

265
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:07,000
is a hot topic of debate within consciousness studies right now.

266
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:10,000
I don't have time to deal with any more of these dogmas,

267
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:12,000
but every single one of them is questionable.

268
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:17,000
If one questions it, new forms of research, new possibilities open up.

269
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:21,000
And I think as we question these dogmas that have held back science so long,

270
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:25,000
science will undergo a reflaring, a renaissance.

271
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:27,000
I'm a total believer in the importance of science.

272
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:31,000
I've spent my whole life as a research scientist, my whole career.

273
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:35,000
But I think by moving beyond these dogmas, it can be regenerated.

274
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:39,000
Once again, it can become interesting and I hope life affirming.

275
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:41,000
Thank you.

276
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:03,000
Thank you.

277
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:33,000
Thank you.

